t canon formation in Canada? How have different genres fared in the creation of literary anthologies? How do Canadian anthologies transmit ideas about gender, region, ideology, and nation? Specific essays focus on anthologies as national metaphors, the controversies surrounding early literary collections, representations of First Nations peoples in anthologies, and the ways in which various editors have understood exploration narratives. In addition, the collection examines the representation of women in Canadian anthologies, the use of anthologies as teaching tools, and the creation of some very odd Canadian anthologies along the way.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 0aAnthologiesxHistoire et critique. 0aAnthologiesxHistory and criticism. 0aCanada dans la littérature. 0aCanadian literature (English)xHistory and criticism. 0aCanadian literaturexHistory and criticismxTheory, etc. 0aCanadiens dans la littérature. 0aCanon (Literature). 0aChefs-d'oeuvre (Littérature). 0aLittérature canadienne-anglaisexHistoire et critique. 0aNational characteristics, Canadian, in literature. 4aLiterary Criticism. 4aLiterary Criticism: Canadian Literature. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Canadian.2bisacsh1 aBentley, D. M. R., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCavell, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCompton, Anne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCundell, Cheryl, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavey, Frank, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeshaye, Joel, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFee, Margery, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFriskney, Janet B., econtributor.4ct